{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526400"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:22:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:22:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14132"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14132"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.03,0.15,0.03,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6812"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113471"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6812"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14132"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95492"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40147"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43932"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46994"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113471"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of fatigue, nausea, and dark urine. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He denies any recent travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly unwell. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. His sclera are icteric and his abdomen is tender in the right upper quadrant. Investigations reveal ALT 450 U/L (5-40), AST 350 U/L (5-40), and total bilirubin 65 \u00b5mol/L (3-20). Serology shows positive IgM anti-HAV antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most relevant to determining the likely source of infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["History of recreational drug use","History of animal contact","Sexual history","Country of birth","Food consumption over the past five days"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis A is a virus that is primarily transmitted via the faecal-oral route, causing an acute hepatitis. In this case of acute infection in a man with no recent travel history, the \u003Cstrong\u003Esexual history\u003C/strong\u003E is most relevant to determining the likely source of infection. In non-endemic areas, sexual transmission, particularly among men who have sex with men (MSM), has become an increasingly important route of hepatitis A virus (HAV) transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFood consumption over the past five days\u003C/strong\u003E is worth considering as HAV is able to survive many food storage methods, leading to multiple outbreaks in the past related to imported and frozen foods. However, as HAV has an incubation period of 15-50 days, food consumption over the past five days is less relevant than exposures from several weeks prior. Food-borne outbreaks of hepatitis A in Australia are rare, with fewer than five reported outbreaks per year nationally. Most hepatitis A cases in Australia are now associated with travel to endemic areas or person-to-person transmission rather than food-borne sources.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistory of recreational drug use\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly intravenous drug use, can be associated with hepatitis infections. Intravenous and other drug use is a risk factor for hepatitis A infection due to associated social and environmental factors, however unlike hepatitis C and B is not usually a mechanism of transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistory of animal contact\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant risk factor for hepatitis A infection. While some animals can carry certain strains of hepatitis E, hepatitis A is primarily a human disease and is not typically transmitted from animals to humans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECountry of birth\u003C/strong\u003E can be relevant in understanding potential past exposure to hepatitis A, especially if the patient was born in or has lived in an endemic area. However, given that this patient has no recent travel history, and the infection is acute, the country of birth is less likely to be the immediate source of infection compared to more recent exposures. This history would be more relevant to hepatitis B infection, where country of birth may increase suspicion for previous exposure and chronic infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of hepatitis A is primarily supportive, as there is no specific antiviral treatment. The public health response includes contact tracing to identify and provide post-exposure prophylaxis to close contacts. This may involve administration of hepatitis A vaccine or immunoglobulin within two weeks of exposure. Patients should also be advised that during the infectious period they should not have sexual contact or prepare food or drinks for others, and should practice safe hygiene practices include handwashing and cleaning of the toilet seat after use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The consumption of contaminated food or water, particularly when travelling in endemic areas, is a key transmission pathway of hepatitis A; however it is important to consider hepatitis A\u0027s long incubation period","Sexual contact, particularly among men who have sex with men, is an important mode of hepatitis A transmission in non-endemic areas.","Public health response to hepatitis A includes contact tracing, post-exposure prophylaxis, and education about prevention measures."],"references":["Hepatitis A. In: STI Guidelines Australia [online] 2024. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/hepatitis-a/","Hepatitis A control guideline. In: NSW Health [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.health.nsw.gov.au:443/Infectious/controlguideline/Pages/hepa.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95492"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14132"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95492"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-12T10:49:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-12T10:52:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6812"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113471"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"r